So excited to see international cooperation in action ‚ù§Ô∏è #ocdeforum  __________________________  OECD Forum 2019: World in EMotion¬† This year‚Äôs OECD Forum gives stakeholders from academia  business  civil society  and government the chance to connect and share their ideas around four main themes : ‚Ä¢	A New Social Contract ‚Ä¢	Integrity and Trust ‚Ä¢	Digitalisation and the Future of Work ‚Ä¢	International co-operation  The discussions around these themes will reflect on the deep social  economic and political upheaval and disruption we experience today  largely amplified by the dual forces of digitalisation and globalisation. The Forum will explore ways to transform these expressions of uncertainty and anger into a collective commitment for positive action.  I‚Äôm so grateful the #oecdforum exists. And ask the question: what can we do together?

Our 2019 Global Voices Scholars have arrived and are ready for a big week few days of interactive sessions as part of the @the_oecd #oecdforum  The OECD Forum was created in 2000 to discuss the key economic and social challenges on the international agenda.  This 2-day public engagement event gathers high-level government representatives  CEOs  leaders from civil society and trade unions as well as prominent members of academia and media.  With a theme this year of ‚ÄòWORLD IN eMOTION‚Äô we‚Äôre excited to engage in discussions this week and contribute a youth perspective.

In 2014  Global Forest Watch ushered in a new era of radical transparency for the world‚Äôs forests.  With the click of a button  anyone can now see when and where trees are disappearing anywhere in the world. This information is generated in near-real time using satellite data  advanced computer algorithms  and the cloud computing power of Google.  Over 1.5 million people from every country in the world have now used Global Forest Watch for many purposes  including law enforcement  supply chain management  investigative journalism  NGO campaigns  community forestry  and education. #oecdforum

#OECD #OECDFORUM  Day 2  OECD launched the Outlook. China is implied to pose major risk on the sustainability of global growth. Are people convinced by OECD?  I make three points to Mr. Angel Gurria  the Secretary General. First  OECD should at least invite an expert on China-s growth since the Outlook has covered so much about China.  Second  the probability of any projection that happens in reality is zero  which calls for cautious interpretation.  Third  since China-s growth will inevitably regress to the mean  its slowing down will be the new scenario faced by everyone. OECD should provide unbiased judgement  intriguing insight  and practical advice for us all for this new scenario.
